metadata.name: stigmergy #177
metadata.description:
Stigmergy is a method of decentralized organization in which agents communicate by leaving traces in a shared environment. This piece simulates a kind of stigmergy among a large population of particles. Each particle leaves a trail behind it as it moves, and determines its direction of motion based on the trails around it. The rules for how a particle should move based on its surroundings were created with a user-guided evolutionary process.

Press "c" to capture a 2048x2048 image of the simulation. You can also press the spacebar to pause/unpause the simulation, and press "n" while paused to move the simulation forward a single step.

metadata.name: Primitifs systÃ©matiques #5
metadata.description:
Primitifs systÃ©matiques is the first generative instalment of David Umemotoâ€™s studies of space and volume. Placed at the crux of brutalism and minimalism, these structures based on the original stackable concrete piece Primitif 04 evoke impossible paths yet to be explored. 

The original Primitif 04 has been both preserved and dented, conserved and enhanced. It is still here. But it cannot be found, only encountered. Throughout your explorations of the Primitifs systÃ©matiques, you will find that its original shapes have been multiplied, rotated, re-ordered to create new structures. After spending some time exploring its paths, when you stop looking for it, you will realize that 04 is still here, intact.

Lines of work chosen for this piece also draw a perspective. The orientation of the primitives pulls directly towards an intense source of light. Sometimes it is visible, sometimes it is not. This perfect alignment is a call to life. They who look at the sunrise with relief cannot be anything but hopeful. But how can we project life on a concrete behemoth? Stand long enough in front of it, and you too will see that we have no choice but to.

----

Primitifs systÃ©matiques is the generative art genesis piece of David Umemoto. It was built in collaboration with Anaglyphic. It is the first collaborative spatial token made available on the anaver.se.

metadata.name: 7 Years of Bad Luck #55
metadata.description:
## Flavor text 
Supposedly it all started with the Romans. When breaking a mirror your soul would be cursed. Fortunately, the Romans also believed that the soul renews every 7 years. So actually, breaking a mirror brings you at most 7 years of bad luck, but I supposed the "at most" part was dropped because it didn't sound as cool.

## The Algorithm
The mirror shards are created by recursively breaking up a base shape into smaller pieces. Once the mirror is broken each shard is displaced. This is not a packing algorithm.

The texture is created using domain warped Perlin noise.

## Main Features
- 26 color palettes.
- 3 types shape groups (square, 5-10-sided-polygon, circle).
- 4 levels of 'brokenness' -- the number of mirror shards.
- 2 methods for breaking up the shards.

metadata.name: Confini #91
metadata.description:
This is my last fxhash piece for a while, so that I can focus on my personal life. I tried to make a piece that creates the appearance of shapes scratched into the canvas. There are three carefully selected color palettes. One of them is heavily inspired by "Self-Portrait with Bandaged Ear and Pipe", by Van Gogh. These are heavily contrasting colors that I tried to get to work in coherence. One of the color palettes exists out of flavorful colors and means to spark joy in the viewer (depending on the outcome). The final color palette is one that is meant to evoke nothing but calmness. The colors are meant to remind of nature and serenity. I hope you enjoy my work.

Made in p5.js

By twistie

metadata.name: Refractions #275
metadata.description:
Refractions is a study of frequencies, harmonies and abstract representations of natural phenomena. 

It is an experiment of blending three colors to create integrated textural compositions.


Probabilities;

- 14 compositions with variations.

- 2 background color.

- 19 different base color palette (2 monochrome).

- 2 distinct textures with variations.

-  2 different alpha types; tangential & sinusoidal.

- Different edges.

- Several starting positions and styles (wavy or straight).

metadata.name: Chop Chop #134
metadata.description:
Chop Chop is a complementary collection to Caterpillars that I prepared to thank my collectors for the amazing love and interest you showed to my work. I did not want to force my way to your wallets with unsolicited thank-you nfts, so all holders of Caterpillars will have a reserve spot to mint at least 1 tokens per wallet for 0 tez ( I dont understand the reserve options fully, sorry - 128 editions reserved for holders of Caterpillars) . 

The holders of this collection will have reserve spots for my next  collection. The reserve spots will be held for one week from minting, and I prefer the unreserved editions to be fair game for anyone, so first come, first served.

I decided to re-work this older project of mine because it was going to take some time for me to prepare an independent and novel collection and also wanted to continue learning new things. The concept is Paul Klee meets Vector Math and Flow Fields, as you can see the visuals are heavily inspired by Paul Klee's work :)

Under the hood, the circles and triangles act as repulsive forces that break and distort the grid, and push the squares in their range out of their way, forming some holes in the fabric created by the same algo that made Caterpillars. 

I have only added one rarity feature which is the palette because this one uses almost all the palettes from Caterpillars (minus neon dreams). I am hoping that this project will not be about rarity, but more like a thank-you gift and an easy way to access my future work.

Well, I hope you will like it...

- Press "s" to save a png.

- Also, 33% royalty split wth the Processing Foundation, % 33 with the minters (if there will be any secondary sales) 

DISCLAIMER :
I am very very new to coding and not very good at this. I have tried to clean up the code as best as I could, and I hope that there is nothing terribly wrong left inside.

metadata.name: sandspiral II #152
metadata.description: This is a re-imagining of my new forms 04: sand spirals mint from hic et nunc in April '21. (https://hen.hicathon.xyz/objkt/68268 ). It has been altered to produce unique mints. There are 12 different random traits seeded from the operation hash, but only four are visible: primary hue, secondary hue, initial rotation, and line width. All values are equal likelihood, so there is no "rarity" per se; aesthetic value is the only trait that matters.
